            <summary>
              <p>François Déroche schreibt zum Fragment KFQ 29 (Déroche,  <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/QJQEKNSJ" sameAs="QJQEKNSJ" type="zotero">The Abbasid Tradition, London 1992</ref>, S. 82): "32 / Single folio / 9th century AD / 15.8 x 20.7 cm, with 15 lines to the page / <hi rend="italic">Material</hi> Parchment; the verso is the hair side / <hi rend="italic">Text</hi> <hi rend="italic">area</hi> 10.5 x 16.5 cm / <hi rend="italic">Script</hi> Related to style D.IV / <hi rend="italic">Accession</hi> <hi rend="italic">no</hi>. KFQ 29 / This folio contains <hi rend="italic">Sūrat</hi> <hi rend="italic">al-baqarah</hi> (II), verses 107-115. The text is written in brown ink, with the diacritical strokes, which are mainly additions, in black. Red dots indicate the vowels. The verses are divided by a I.I.I device of three oblique strokes, and a 2’.A.II illumination at verse III marks the end of a group of ten verses. / The last word of the preceding folio has been written in a later cursive hand in the upper margin of the recto, and the first word of the following folio in the lower margin of the verso; this may have been done during a restoration.”</p>
            </summary>
